[2] The hazards of hindsight conclusions
Date: Fri 19 Jun 2020 21:00 BST
Source: The Guardian [edited]
https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jun/19/our-knowledge-of-covid-19-changes-every-day-hindsight-is-misleading-when-it-comes-to-science


The results of a COVID-19 study have been announced. Unlike most of the previous results, this study seems immediately to be a game-changer -- rather than minor benefits from an expensive drug, or spurious nonsense from a dubious trial, these results show that a cheap and common medication, dexamethasone, could reduce the risk of death in people with severe disease by a substantial amount. The study was large enough to be meaningful and its finding likely to be true. This is, without qualification, fantastic news.

But immediately people started commenting. Had we known about this drug sooner, they said, 5000 lives could have been saved in the UK alone. The reasoning here appears to be that, because the drug prevents roughly 1 in 8 deaths from COVID-19, and because 40 000 people have died in the UK, you could have saved 12.5%, or 5000, of those people if you had treated them with this drug from the start.

Now that idea is fairly misleading -- it's a misapplication of the number needed to treat, and it ignores the reasonable likelihood that many patients were treated with dexamethasone or an equivalent drug anyway -- but it speaks to a larger point that we all need to be wary of: the issue of hindsight. It may be very tempting for us all to look back, in the months and years to come, and say "if only we had known this when ... " but the problem with these statements is that they ignore the realities of science.

Take the World Health Organization, for example. Many people have attacked it for saying in a tweet, on [14 Jan 2020], that there was no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission of the novel coronavirus. It's easy to look back now and say "well, that was obviously wrong", but if you actually look at the evidence that the WHO was working from at the time that statement was entirely correct. While we can argue about how forthcoming China was being in early January [2020], any scientist working from the information available would've been cautious, because there were simply too many unknowns to be sure of anything.

And broadly speaking, that's true of most things. We know now that hydroxychloroquine almost certainly doesn't work in treating COVID-19, with major clinical trials halted after finding no benefit, but that doesn't mean that we've wasted the last 3 months. It would have been enormously unscientific, not to mention unethical, to decide on the basis of incomplete information that one drug worked and simply start using it.

In fact, these hindsight comments ignore the truly breathtaking scientific effort that has taken place in 2020. If you had asked me only a year ago [2019] whether I thought that a 100-country trial involving patients in the tens of thousands could be set up and run within a month, I would've laughed -- the idea would've been preposterous. And yet that's almost exactly what the WHO has done in its Solidarity trial. The fact that we have seen results from thousands of patients carefully randomised into treatment arms within weeks of the study beginning is nothing short of miraculous and speaks to the truly astonishing effort that these researchers have put in to find out what does and doesn't work against COVID-19.

We can't look back and wonder what might have been, because the path that we've trodden was really the only one available. Perhaps in the next pandemic, we'll see science move even more quickly but, given the sheer number of papers published on the coronavirus since the year [2020] began, perhaps not.

The reality is that, while hindsight might be fun, it is misleading. Our knowledge of COVID-19 is changing every day, and it will continue to do so for years to come. You can't look back and wonder what if -- not just because it ignores the scientific process, but also because what we know now will probably be obsolete within weeks. In 2020 science has gone from a gradual accumulation of knowledge to a train at full steam. It's worth remembering that what is true today will almost certainly be proven false next week, and that when people appear to change their minds it is an inherently good thing -- adapting to new evidence is the cornerstone of science.

Ultimately, it is probably folly to think about the things we could've known. That's not to say that there weren't mistakes, things we could've done better -- obviously not everything went entirely to plan -- but that examining our failures with current knowledge simply doesn't make sense. We must always remember, when looking back, that there were so many things that we didn't -- and still don't -- know.

[Byline: Gideon Meyerowitz-Katz]

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[These are words that needed to be said to remind all of us not to jump to severe criticism using 2020 hindsight. The reminder of the criticism of WHO's tweet, when the information available supported the tweet is something to keep in mind. And the warning that the plethora of scientific articles, many pre-peer reviewed that would not pass the peer review process leads folks down the garden path to draw conclusions only to be withdrawn as rigorous studies prove them wrong. The blame game grows tiresome to read. 20/20 hindsight is helpful to develop lessons learned moving forward, which should be the outcome of retrospective studies looking at what worked and what didn't work during the pandemic. One lesson learned late was the true stealth nature of this virus. Unlike its cousin's, the SARS-CoV-1 and MERS-CoV, peak viral loads are pre-symptomatic, and that pre- and asymptomatic individuals have been implicated in transmission chains. The world learned the hard way, overlooking asymptomatic contacts for testing in the early days... but that's a takeaway lesson learned when dealing with new organisms... seek and ye shall find... - Mod.MPP]

