[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 50.6% of the global newly reported cases and 63.3% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. The USA reported 40.9% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, Brazil reported 25.9%, Mexico 7.9%, Chile 6.8%, and Peru 5.3%. The same 5 countries remained at the top, with changing orders... the USA and Brazil are usually numbers 1 and 2 although they vary for which of the 2 positions they hold.

The European region reported 14.1% of the global newly reported cases and 11.1% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 39.3% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Sweden 15.3%, Turkey 6.4%, the UK 5.1%, Ukraine 4.4%, Belarus 2.7%, and Germany 2.7%. Again, the same countries with the addition of Sweden, minor juggling of orders and percentages day by day, although the proportion of cases represented by Russia has fallen.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 13.9% of the global newly reported cases and 12.1% of global newly reported fatalities. Pakistan reported 21.3% of the regional newly reported cases followed by Saudi Arabia 18.3%, Iran 13.9%, Iraq 9.8%, Oman 8.7%, Egypt 8.5%, and Qatar 5.6%. Same countries, minor juggling of positions (Oman and Egypt switched positions).

The African region reported 5.7% of the global newly reported cases and 3.1% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 56.9% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 8.9%, Cameroon 8.1%, Gabon 4.1%, Cote d'Ivoire 2.5%, Mauritania 2.3%, and Central African Republic 2.1%. While South Africa and Nigeria are usually numbers 1 and 2 in terms of the 24-hour increase in cases, other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day although Cameroon, Central African Republic, and Mauritania bear watching.

The Western Pacific region reported 0.78% of the global newly reported cases and 0.29% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 60.8% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Singapore 21.0%, Japan and China 5.0% each, and South Korea 4.4%. The outbreak associated with the Beijing Seafood markets continues to bring China to prominence in terms of daily newly confirmed cases. That said, the Philippines and Singapore are consistently numbers 1 and 2, respectively, and the other countries, including Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, and Australia, vary in daily reporting.

The South East Asia region reported 14.9% of the global newly reported cases and 10.0% of global deaths. India reported 74.9% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 17.5%, Indonesia 4.8%, and Nepal 2.7%. Same countries, same order as in previous days, with India continuing to be the driving force in the regional growth in cases.

Impression: Europe seems to be stabilizing at a significantly lower rate, although Russia is still reporting 7000+ new cases a day (down from 8000+ per day). The Eastern Mediterranean had surpassed the European region in the past few days, but is slightly behind today (23 Jun 2020), with Pakistan reporting around 4000+ cases a day (over 3900 today 23 Jun 2020) and Saudi Arabia reporting around 4000+ cases a day (over 3300 today 23 Jun 2020). South East Asia has overtaken both the European and Eastern Mediterranean regions, with India reporting 8000-10 000+ cases a day (over 14 000 cases today 23 Jun 2020). The Americas region is usually reporting around 70 000 cases a day (over 67 000 cases today 23 Jun 2020), with Brazil usually reporting 25 000-30 000+ cases a day (over 17 000 cases today 23 Jun 2020) and the USA at 20 000-25 000+ a day (over 27 000 today 23 Jun 2020). In the Africa region, the regional proportion is slowly climbing, with South Africa reporting in the 3000-4000+ range daily, and the Western Pacific region is maintaining a very low rate compared with the other regions, with the Philippines averaging 500+ cases per day (over 600 cases today 23 Jun 2020). (Singapore had been reporting twice as many cases per day for a period of time but has dropped back over the past couple of weeks).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 23 Jun 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South East Asia, in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting. - Mod.MPP]

